    <h1>VITAMIN C</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201023/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-23"><time>2020-10-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | STYLE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Pos­si­bly one of the most-pop­u­lar ac­tive in­gre­di­ents con­sumers are fa­mil­iar with, vitamin C de­liv­ers just as many ben­e­fits when ap­plied top­i­cally as when taken in your or­ange juice.</p>
    <p>It is most of­ten touted as a bright­en­ing agent that works to in­hibit melanin pro­duc­tion, which causes dark spots and hy­per­pig­men­ta­tion.</p>
    <p>As an an­tiox­i­dant, it pro­tects skin against harm­ful free rad­i­cals caused by ex­po­sure to ul­tra­vi­o­let light.</p>
    <p>When in­cor­po­rat­ing it into your skin­care reg­i­men, opt for serums and look for L-ascor­bic acid forms of vitamin C – the most po­tent form of vitamin C in skin­care.</p>
    <p>For op­ti­mised re­sults, ap­ply in the day­time be­neath sun­screen to stay pro­tected through­out the day.</p>
    <p>TRY:</p>
    <p>1. In­n­is­free Bright­en­ing Pore Serum 30ml, $52 2. Kiehl’s Pow­er­fulStrengt­h Line-Re­duc­ing & Dark Cir­cleDi­min­ish­ing Vitamin C</p>
    <p>Eye Serum, $75</p>

